ers, now in the French département of Nord), which have the same etymology, are alternative possibilities but seem less likely on geographical and tenurial grounds.","English: perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>crus(e)</i> ‘bold, fierce’, although the regular development would be to <i>Crowse</i> (rhyming with <i>house</i>).","North German: variant of   Krause  ."]}]},{"name":"Aveline","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It seems to represent an Old French pet form of the Germanic name   Avila   (a derivative of   Avis  ), but it could also be an elaborated form of   Ava ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":10,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":41,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Aveline de Cruce was born in 1249, in Prestbury, Cheshire, England, her father, Geoffrey de Cruce, was 24 and her mother, Joan de Saunford, was 22. She married Roger Legh in 1268, in Prestbury, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1299, in Cheshire, England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1249–1299":"1249–1299","1240–1278":"1240–1278","1269–1325":"1269–1325","1225–1249":"1225–1249","1227–1278":"1227–1278","1249":"